SIMPLE: globulin
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Globulin
<hw>Glob"u*lin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From
<er>Globule</er>: cf. F. <ets>globuline</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Phisiol.
Chem.)</fld> <def>An albuminous body, insoluble in water, but soluble in
dilute solutions of salt. It is present in the red blood corpuscles
united with h⟦ae⟧matin to form h⟦ae⟧moglobin. It is also found in the
crystalline lens of the eye, and in blood serum, and is sometimes called
<xex>crystallin</xex>. In the plural the word is applied to a group of
proteid substances such as vitellin, myosin, fibrinogen, etc., all
insoluble in water, but soluble in dilute salt solutions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Globulite</ent>⟦br⟧
